> We've taken the best pork loin we could lay our hands on from our Butcher Nick 'The Knife' and teamed it up with super nutritious sweet potato mash. If you've got peppercorns in the cupboard then given them a whack and add them to your sauce - or otherwise you can leave them out - it'll still taste crazy good!

Take the @pork medallion{1} out of the #fridge{} to come to room temperature. Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} and pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees. Peel the @sweet potato{2} and cut into rough 2cm cubes. Separate the @broccoli{1} florets from the stalk (you can also peel, chop and cook the stalk).

Boil the sweet potato for around ~{10-15%mins} or until soft. Lift the potatoes from the water once done and keep the water for the broccoli. Mash the sweet potatoes with a good pinch of salt and pepper. Stir through a tsp of @?butter{1%tsp} (if you have some) or a tbsp of @crème fraîche{1%tbsp}.

Meanwhile cover your pork fillet with a good pinch of salt and pepper. Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot add in the pork fillet and cook for a couple of mins on each side until it has nicely browned off.

Transfer the fillet to a #baking tray{} and cook in the oven for ~{15%mins}.

> Do not wash up your frying pan as we'll use it to make your sauce tastier later.

Once cooked, take it out of the oven and leave it to rest for a few mins.

Cook the broccoli in the water left over from the potatoes (if you need to top it up a little bit that's ok). Cook for a few mins and then remove from the water. Save some water for your sauce!

== Sauce ==

To make your sauce put your used frying pan back on medium-high heat. Once it gets hot add @water{200%ml} of the water from the broccoli and stir in @beef stock pot{1/2}. Once the sauce reduces by half, take it from the heat and let it cool for ~{2%mins}. Stir through @crème fraîche{2%tbsp}.

If you want to spice up your sauce, crush @?black peppercorns{1/2%tsp} in a #pestle and mortar{}.

> If you don't have a pestle and mortar you can put them in clingfilm and whack them with a pan.

Add the crushed peppercorns to your sauce at the same time as the stock.

== To Serve ==

Slice the pork and serve everything straight away with your sauce. YUM!